Wash and dry all produce. Bring a #medium pot{} of water to a boil. Peel @ginger{1%thumb}, then finely mince or grate. Peel @carrots{2}, then very thinly slice on a diagonal. Thinly slice @garlic{2%cloves}. Trim, then thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating greens and whites. Mince @chili pepper{1}, removing ribs and seeds first for less heat.

Whisk together @soy sauce{4%tablespoon}, @sherry vinegar{5%teaspoon}, @orange jam{2%tablespoon}, 1/4 cup water, and @cornstarch{1%tablespoon} in a #small bowl{}. Set aside.

Once water boils, separate out @yakisoba noodles{8%ounce} (about 2 1/2 cups or half the package; save the rest for another use). Add to #pot{} and cook until just tender, about ~{2%minutes}. Drain, then rinse in #colander{} under cool running water. Toss with a drizzle of @vegetable oil{3%teaspoon} and set aside.

Roughly chop @coconut crunch cashews{1%ounce} into smaller pieces.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add garlic, ginger, scallion whites, @coriander{1%teaspoon}, and half the chili. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Toss in @shredded red cabbage{4%ounce} and carrots. Cook, tossing, until cabbage wilts and carrots are tender, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Add noodles to pan. Using #tongs{}, toss noodles into the other ingredients. Pour in soy sauce mixture, toss again with tongs, and cook until noodles are coated in a sticky sauce. Remove pan from heat. Divide noodle stir-fry between plates. Garnish with scallion greens, cashews, and remaining chili to taste.

> TIP: If you're not a fan of spice, use less of or skip the chili.